ir Transport Command","notes":"Pilot for Air Transport Command during WWII."},{"role":"Director","organization":"Canadair Ltd","location":"Montréal"},{"role":"Vice President","organization":"Scandinavian Airlines System (SAS)","location":"Sweden","notes":"Spent 5 years in Sweden organizing the Scandinavian Air Industry. Knighted by kings of Denmark, Norway, and Sweden for his contribution to aviation and SAS."}],"military_service":[{"war":"World War II","war_id":"WAR008","unit":"Air Transport Command","notes":"Pilot for Air Transport Command WWII."}],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["wwii","canada_migration","new_york_migration","washington_state_migration"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Knighted by three Scandinavian kings for aviation","body":"Peter Harold Redpath flew as TWA co-pilot, served as Air Transport Command pilot in World War II, directed Canadair Limited in Montreal, and spent five years in Sweden organizing the Scandinavian Air Industry as Vice President of Scandinavian Airlines. He was knighted by the kings of Denmark, Norway, and Sweden for his contributions to aviation and SAS — three royal knighthoods earned in a single career."},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"Died in mid-flight emergency landing Chicago 1977","body":"Peter Harold Redpath died November 8, 1977 of a heart attack aboard a Northwest Airlines flight from Minneapolis to New York. The pilot diverted to O'Hare International after a flight attendant noticed him slumped in his seat; he died at a Chicago hospital. He was a Bellingham Washington resident since 1961, a director of the Whatcom County Museum Foundation Board, and active in the Bellingham Yacht Club and Rotary Club."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"peter-redpath-1902"},"HD4202":{"id":"HD4202","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":fal